With man alone the brain throbs in infancy, and does not become firm before the child first begins to talk. The brain is the highest of the organs in position, and it is protected by the vault of the head3 it has no flesh or blood or refuse. It is the citadel of sense- perception, and the focus to which all the flow of the veins converges from the heart and at which it stops; it is the crowning pinnacle, the seat of government of the mind. But the brain of all animals slopes forward‚ because our senses also stretch in front of us. It is the source of sleep and the cause of drowsy nodding3 species without a brain do not sleep.
